This list was put together by someone who's been on the other side of the deals.

3
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:18,160
He's acquired tens of millions of dollars worth of mobile apps and personally talked to close to 2,000 app builders across the last 5 years.

4
00:00:18,160 --> 00:00:22,640
And a lot of these builders you've probably also seen right here on this channel.

5
00:00:22,640 --> 00:00:24,560
I speak to about 10 founders a week.

6
00:00:24,560 --> 00:00:27,680
Everything from your beginner to the guy who just hit 10K MR.

7
00:00:27,680 --> 00:00:31,279
And I see a lot of guys making mistakes and not quite getting it right.

8
00:00:31,279 --> 00:00:32,960
His name is Josh.

9
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:39,200
And what makes him uniquely qualified to give you this list right here is that he doesn't build apps.

10
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:45,200
He buys them for millions, which means he sees something most founders never get to see.

11
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:49,120
What the other side of the table, the acquirers, actually care about.

12
00:00:49,120 --> 00:01:00,000
So, I asked Josh to come on to the channel and share these seven rules every app builder needs to follow if they want to build to sell and not just build for side income.

13
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:03,039
All right, this one is important and let's get into it.

14
00:01:03,039 --> 00:01:04,400
I'm Pat Walls.

15
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:06,880
Welcome to Starter Story Build.

16
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:08,640
All right, Josh, welcome to the channel.

17
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:11,200
Tell me about your experience buying apps.

18
00:01:11,200 --> 00:01:16,240
>> For the last 5 years, I've been writing million-doll checks for a variety of different mobile businesses.

19
00:01:16,240 --> 00:01:20,320
In gaming, I had a budget of up to 150 million to buy mobile games.

20
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:26,000
And now in consumer apps, I've deployed over $23 million into exceptional app founders.

21
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:28,320
This means I speak to about 10 founders a week.

22
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:33,200
Everything from your beginner to the guy who just hit 10K MR to the guy who already sold his business.

23
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:38,960
So today I want to talk about the seven rules that end up separating the great founders from the good founders.

24
00:01:38,960 --> 00:01:41,280
That's why I'm really excited to have you on here.

25
00:01:41,280 --> 00:01:42,799
You talk to a lot of founders.

26
00:01:42,799 --> 00:01:50,720
You see apps that gets sold for millions and then you see apps that are making a bunch of money or not making a bunch of money and they never sell for anything.

27
00:01:50,720 --> 00:01:53,280
So that's why I'm really excited to have you on to share this.

28
00:01:53,280 --> 00:02:02,240
Anybody watching this can walk away with a few things that they can do today and over the next month and over the next year so that they can sell a business and have a lifechanging exit.

29
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:03,600
So let's dive in.

30
00:02:03,600 --> 00:02:04,560
What's the first rule?

31
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:09,200
>> Rule number one is value proposition beats category every time.

32
00:02:09,200 --> 00:02:16,239
Everyone always asks me when they starting to build their first app, they say, "What category should I build in to hit my first 5K in MR?"

33
00:02:16,239 --> 00:02:19,360
And the honest answer is it actually doesn't matter.

34
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:25,040
You can make a ton of money with a PDF scanner app the same way you can make a ton of money with a step counter app.

35
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:29,840
The truth is that your value proposition matters a lot more than the category you're building in.

36
00:02:29,840 --> 00:02:36,160
Your value proposition is the pain point you're solving for the user and it's the reason why you probably set out to build in the first place.

37
00:02:36,160 --> 00:02:37,599
So, how do you actually do this?

38
00:02:37,599 --> 00:02:42,239
The best tip I can give is to launch your app from day one with a premium tier.

39
00:02:42,239 --> 00:02:46,400
Don't wait until you have the perfect amount of downloads or you're waiting for product market fit.

40
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:53,840
The question you want to answer as a founder in the beginning as soon as possible is do people see value in paying for my app.

41
00:02:53,840 --> 00:02:57,440
If the answer is no, you need to increase the value of your premium tier.

42
00:02:57,440 --> 00:02:59,280
Number two, you can lower the price.

43
00:02:59,280 --> 00:03:01,519
Or number three, you might have to pivot completely.

44
00:03:01,519 --> 00:03:06,480
One mistake I saw a founder make last month in a conversation was he hadn't played with his pricing.

45
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:10,959
And this is something you should be testing cuz this has one of the biggest impacts on your revenue.

46
00:03:10,959 --> 00:03:12,560
>> Okay, what's the next rule?

47
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:14,000
>> Go hand solo, guys.

48
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:20,319
It's 2026 and if you're just starting and you're waiting for the perfect co-founder to come along and be your partner,

49
00:03:20,319 --> 00:03:20,879
stop.

50
00:03:20,879 --> 00:03:27,040
Because to go from zero to 10K or 50K or a million ARR, you don't need the best UI UX designer.

51
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:30,239
You don't need the best product guy and you don't need the best codebase.

52
00:03:30,239 --> 00:03:35,519
All you need today is an app that solves a real problem and one proven distribution channel.

53
00:03:35,519 --> 00:03:40,080
This channel can be Reddit, can be Tik Tok, it can be Meta, can be Google, it doesn't matter.

54
00:03:40,080 --> 00:03:41,760
So, let's simplify all of this.

55
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:46,080
If you're watching this and you're stuck, here's your co-founding team to build a consumer.

56
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:51,840
First of all, screenesign.com to design it, Rock or Claude to build it, Tik Tok to market it,

57
00:03:51,840 --> 00:03:53,440
revenue to monetize it.

58
00:03:53,440 --> 00:03:58,879
For example, the other day I was talking to a cracked 22-year-old founder who built an app in the religion niche.

59
00:03:58,879 --> 00:04:00,400
This guy built the thing on rock.

60
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:03,519
He used Tik Tok to go absolutely viral and the thing went crazy.

61
00:04:03,519 --> 00:04:04,560
The thing went parabolic.

62
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:06,799
He was doing 2 millionaire raw within 6 months.

63
00:04:06,799 --> 00:04:12,080
And >> that's what I'm seeing too is that these AI tools lower the barrier to entry to get started.

64
00:04:12,080 --> 00:04:12,959
You don't need a designer.

65
00:04:12,959 --> 00:04:14,159
You don't need a back-end engineer.

66
00:04:14,159 --> 00:04:15,439
You don't need a front-end engineer.

67
00:04:15,439 --> 00:04:18,639
All you really need is a good idea in a good market as you shared.

68
00:04:18,639 --> 00:04:19,759
What's the next rule?

69
00:04:19,759 --> 00:04:27,280
>> Rule number three is you got to think beyond the MR because MR will pay your bills and that's super important especially in the early days.

70
00:04:27,280 --> 00:04:32,479
But for someone to come along and pay seven figures for your app, they need to understand what's behind the MR.

71
00:04:32,479 --> 00:04:34,960
And the answer to that question is the product metrics.

72
00:04:34,960 --> 00:04:36,720
How healthy is your consumer app?

73
00:04:36,720 --> 00:04:40,880
So, as an app founder, you've got to remember that if someone is going to pay seven figures for your app,

74
00:04:40,880 --> 00:04:44,800
it's because they believe they can build on the blocks that you've created.

75
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:53,600
Let's simplify all of this because if you've just started out, you've probably got a few metrics that are coming in through your App Store Connect or your Revenue Cat and you're probably sat there thinking,

76
00:04:53,600 --> 00:04:55,520
"All right, these don't look great just yet.

77
00:04:55,520 --> 00:04:56,479
How do I fix them?"

78
00:04:56,479 --> 00:04:59,280
If retention is your problem, then build gamification.

79
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:00,320
I'm talking streaks.

80
00:05:00,320 --> 00:05:02,080
I'm talking daily login rewards.

81
00:05:02,080 --> 00:05:03,520
I'm talking social features.

82
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:04,560
That's how you fix that.

83
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:09,360
If your problem is not enough people are buying your product, introduce some seasonal events,

84
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:14,880
think about Halloween and Christmas with one-time offers and expand the number of prices you're selling at.

85
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:18,400
Third one, if you're looking at your resubscriber rate and you're seeing people churn,

86
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:19,680
I got some bad news for you.

87
00:05:19,680 --> 00:05:22,960
This one is kind of hard to fake and you just need to put in the work.

88
00:05:22,960 --> 00:05:31,360
You need to make sure that your product is actually solving a real problem and that the user feels that the price they paid is worth the value they gained from your app.

89
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:34,800
I love everything that Josh is breaking down right now.

90
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:39,199
How to build apps the right way, especially if you eventually want to sell.

91
00:05:39,199 --> 00:05:42,000
But here's the thing that he said that stuck with me.

92
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,160
You don't need the best UI, the best code base, or even the best product.

93
00:05:46,160 --> 00:05:51,680
You just need an app that solves a problem, and has one proven distribution channel.

94
00:05:51,680 --> 00:05:55,199
So, if you're watching this and thinking, "Okay, I'm ready to build something."

95
00:05:55,199 --> 00:05:57,520
Well, I have just the thing for you.

96
