We will walk you from idea to a real live app on the app store.

98
00:06:07,039 --> 00:06:11,360
And the best part, you don't need any previous experience to get started right now.

99
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:13,280
Josh said it himself.

100
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:15,440
Stop waiting and start building.

101
00:06:15,440 --> 00:06:21,280
So, if you're ready, just head to the link in the description and start building your first app for free.

102
00:06:21,280 --> 00:06:23,680
All right, let's get back to the episode.

103
00:06:23,680 --> 00:06:25,520
Rule number four is keep a clean house.

104
00:06:25,520 --> 00:06:30,960
Because when a buyer comes and they're going to write a check for 7 8 figures, they expect to receive clean,

105
00:06:30,960 --> 00:06:33,680
clear, and organized documentation about your business.

106
00:06:33,680 --> 00:06:35,280
And this can include the technicals.

107
00:06:35,280 --> 00:06:38,400
This can include your financial performance and your product roadmap.

108
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:42,960
And this is so so important because the buyer is about to take responsibility for your baby,

109
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:44,400
the thing you spent years building.

110
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:46,479
But it means the buck now stops with the buyer.

111
00:06:46,479 --> 00:06:48,240
The risk is on the buyer.

112
00:06:48,240 --> 00:06:50,880
So don't panic if you don't have all of this now.

113
00:06:50,880 --> 00:06:52,240
Luckily, it's pretty easy to fix.

114
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:53,280
And let me tell you how.

115
00:06:53,280 --> 00:06:55,680
If you're just starting, document everything.

116
00:06:55,680 --> 00:06:57,759
Keep a P&L, which is a profit and loss.

117
00:06:57,759 --> 00:07:02,960
Keep track of your tools and infrastructure in a Google doc and keep track of where you're spending your marketing money.

118
00:07:02,960 --> 00:07:06,720
Now, if you're already doing a few thousand per month, again, don't stress.

119
00:07:06,720 --> 00:07:10,960
Take one morning, go backwards, build a P&L to the best of your ability.

120
00:07:10,960 --> 00:07:12,800
It doesn't matter if it's not perfect.

121
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:15,759
The most important thing is to be honest and upfront about that.

122
00:07:15,759 --> 00:07:20,960
It's not going to kill the deal, but if you start accurately tracking things now, you're going to thank me later.

123
00:07:20,960 --> 00:07:30,000
I recently sold my business and one thing that I wish I did a little bit more of is just yeah more standardized tools to manage certain things like working with contractors,

124
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,720
working with payroll, taxes and things like that.

125
00:07:32,720 --> 00:07:35,039
So I think that's really important not to reinvent the wheel.

126
00:07:35,039 --> 00:07:39,680
I know there's a temptation to vibe code anything that you would potentially spend money on right now,

127
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:42,639
but if you want to sell your business, I wouldn't be vibe coding tools.

128
00:07:42,639 --> 00:07:48,800
I'd be using industry standard tools that a buyer is comfortable owning that risk after the deal goes through.

129
00:07:48,800 --> 00:07:49,759
So that's a great one.

130
00:07:49,759 --> 00:07:50,639
What's the next rule?

131
00:07:50,639 --> 00:07:53,520
>> Rule number five, I call marketing miles per gallon.

132
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:54,240
Imagine this.

133
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:57,440
Your app is a car and the distance your car travels is your revenue.

134
00:07:57,440 --> 00:08:03,039
Gasoline is your marketing dollars and you want your car to be able to drive as many miles per gallon as possible.

135
00:08:03,039 --> 00:08:03,599
I.e.

136
00:08:03,599 --> 00:08:07,919
you want to create the most revenue with the least amount of marketing dollars.

137
00:08:07,919 --> 00:08:09,039
Why is this important?

138
00:08:09,039 --> 00:08:10,479
Well, let me ask you this.

139
00:08:10,479 --> 00:08:16,639
If you're doing 5K MR, but you're investing 5K into marketing per month, is that a good business?

140
00:08:16,639 --> 00:08:21,840
So try and track your marketing spend and identify the channels that are performing best for you.

141
00:08:21,840 --> 00:08:24,639
When you find the channel that works best for you, double down.

142
00:08:24,639 --> 00:08:28,639
Like I said before, you just need one that works really well, especially for the early days.

143
00:08:28,639 --> 00:08:30,800
So I just bought an app in the education category.

144
00:08:30,800 --> 00:08:37,839
And the one thing I really liked about it that dictated the seven figure outcome was the fact that every time he spent his marketing dollars,

145
00:08:37,839 --> 00:08:39,839
he returned that money within 7 days.

146
00:08:39,839 --> 00:08:40,959
Now that's top tier.

147
00:08:40,959 --> 00:08:44,159
A good benchmark for you guys listening out there who are just getting started.

148
00:08:44,159 --> 00:08:48,480
Anything sub 60 days in the early days is really, really good.

149
00:08:48,480 --> 00:08:51,360
Rule number six is build the relationships early.

150
00:08:51,360 --> 00:09:00,160
I've signed multiple seven and eight figure deals, and honestly, the common denominator that gets the deal over the line every single time is relationship.

151
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:07,600
From my perspective as a buyer, would I rather write a check for $8 million to a founder I've been talking to for 9 months who shared with me their highs,

152
00:09:07,600 --> 00:09:11,279
their lows, and kept me updated, or would I rather write a check to someone I met last week?

153
00:09:11,279 --> 00:09:12,480
Here's what I'd recommend.

154
00:09:12,480 --> 00:09:15,680
Find a few mobile app buyers and send them this exact message.

155
00:09:15,680 --> 00:09:17,920
In fact, take a screenshot of what I'm about to show you.

156
00:09:17,920 --> 00:09:20,560
Hey Josh, I've been building this app for X months.

157
00:09:20,560 --> 00:09:24,640
We've grown Y% month over month, but not without some challenges.

158
00:09:24,640 --> 00:09:28,240
Right now, I'm having a lot of fun growing it, but I know someday I'll sell it.

159
00:09:28,240 --> 00:09:31,200
I'd love to connect to build a relationship for when that time comes.

160
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:35,920
Copy and paste that message to any app buyer you can find, and you'll be in good hands.

161
00:09:35,920 --> 00:09:42,160
We shared this on the starter story acquisition of HubSpot, but it all started with a sponsorship.

162
00:09:42,160 --> 00:09:45,279
They were advertising on our channel and they were one of our biggest partners.

163
00:09:45,279 --> 00:09:49,600
They enjoyed working with us, we enjoyed working with them, and it didn't happen overnight.

164
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:53,839
That relationship was cultivated over the course of years pretty much.

165
00:09:53,839 --> 00:09:57,519
So, similar to what you said is just start relationships generally.

166
00:09:57,519 --> 00:10:02,959
Talk to people, not necessarily just your customers, but buyers like you or other builders,

167
00:10:02,959 --> 00:10:03,920
even competitors.

168
00:10:03,920 --> 00:10:06,320
Build these relationships and amazing things will happen.

169
00:10:06,320 --> 00:10:07,440
So what's the next rule?

170
00:10:07,440 --> 00:10:10,080
>> The last rule is nobody's perfect.

171
00:10:10,080 --> 00:10:12,000
Every business has a sewer.

172
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:15,760
And this is the name I give to those parts of your business that you kind of want to hide.

173
00:10:15,760 --> 00:10:17,440
For an app, it might be bad retention.

174
00:10:17,440 --> 00:10:20,880
It might be high churn rates or a nasty co-founder.

175
00:10:20,880 --> 00:10:22,560
What I'm trying to say is it's okay.

176
00:10:22,560 --> 00:10:24,640
Like no one expects a perfect business.

177
00:10:24,640 --> 00:10:32,560
What I want to stress though is that any buyer who's going to write a check for your business is going to find these sewers during due diligence in a sale.

178
00:10:32,560 --> 00:10:36,959
So honestly, the best piece of advice I can give is to be upfront about the imperfections.

179
00:10:36,959 --> 00:10:41,680
It only helps to build the trust, and these imperfections are going to come out in due diligence anyway.

180
00:10:41,680 --> 00:10:46,000
At the end of last year, I was deep in due diligence with an app that I absolutely loved.

181
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:49,360
We were about 2 weeks out from signing before the founder asked to jump on a call.

182
00:10:49,360 --> 00:10:59,680
On the call, he looked a bit downcast and he basically explained that his relationship with his co-founder was kind of messy and it was going to be kind of difficult to get the deal over the line because of this problem.

183
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:08,560
Now, the fact that he raised this to us and we could work through it together means we actually got the deal over the line instead of something like that blowing the deal up at the end.

184
00:11:08,560 --> 00:11:09,120
>> So true.

185
00:11:09,120 --> 00:11:14,959
I talk to a lot of founders, obviously that's what we do here at Starter Story, and I go and talk to a lot of people that built cool stuff.

186
00:11:14,959 --> 00:11:20,000
And then usually isn't said on camera, but sometimes there's a conversation that goes along like,

187
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:27,120
"Hey, I worked with this guy when we just started out and he believes that he has 50% equity of the business,

188
00:11:27,120 --> 00:11:28,480
even though I built everything."

189
00:11:28,480 --> 00:11:31,279
And then there's this whole legal battle going behind the scenes.

190
00:11:31,279 --> 00:11:41,600
If there is an extra rule that I would like to give to founders is that be very careful with giving out equity in your business and co-founder relationships and building a business with someone that you truly trust and have those

191
00:11:41,600 --> 00:11:42,800
conversations early.

192
00:11:42,800 --> 00:11:44,480
I believe that one's really important too.

193
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:49,360
So my last question for you is for anyone watching this that is in the process of building something right now.

194
00:11:49,360 --> 00:11:51,920
They're about to build something or maybe they're making a little bit of money.

195
00:11:51,920 --> 00:11:58,800
What would be like the top three tips of things you can do right now to maximize your chances to selling for millions?

196
00:11:58,800 --> 00:12:00,560
>> Okay, let's do a quick fire for this one.

197
00:12:00,560 --> 00:12:05,120
Number one, and the product guys are going to kill me for this, you don't need an original idea.

198
00:12:05,120 --> 00:12:07,200
Copy 90% of an app that works.

199
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:09,920
Add 10%, you know, sprinkle in your own innovation.

200
00:12:09,920 --> 00:12:10,720
Off you go.

201
00:12:10,720 --> 00:12:13,200
Number two, guys, monetize from day one.

202
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:16,880
Prove to yourself that the thing you're building, people are willing to pay for.

203
00:12:16,880 --> 00:12:18,000
It's so, so important.

204
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:21,360
Otherwise, you'll find yourself months, years in with no paying customers.

205
00:12:21,360 --> 00:12:24,880
And finally, you only need one marketing channel to work.

206
00:12:24,880 --> 00:12:28,480
You don't need to nail Reddit, Tik Tok, Meta, Google, blah blah blah.

207
00:12:28,480 --> 00:12:30,720
You don't need it, especially in the early days.

208
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:34,000
Find one thing, make it work, double down.

209
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:36,160
>> Before this, we just shot with another founder.

210
00:12:36,160 --> 00:12:39,760
He had a million-doll app, which was purely Android, purely Google ads.

211
00:12:39,760 --> 00:12:40,959
One channel, that's it.

212
00:12:40,959 --> 00:12:43,360
That's all you need to build a business that changes your life.

213
00:12:43,360 --> 00:12:45,600
Thank you for coming on the channel, Josh, and sharing this.

214
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:48,639
I hope to have you back on to talk more about how to sell your business.

215
00:12:48,639 --> 00:12:51,680
It's a very current event over here at Starter Story, so it's awesome.

216
00:12:51,680 --> 00:12:52,959
